{
  "local_port": 42248,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Who are the best angel investors of all time?",
  "response": "Determining the \"best\" angel investors of all time can be subjective, as it depends on criteria such as successful investments, impact on industries, and mentorship to startups. However, several angel investors are widely regarded as influential and successful based on their track records and contributions to the startup ecosystem. Here are some of the most celebrated angel investors:\n\n### 1. **Peter Thiel**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Facebook, LinkedIn, Palantir, Spotify\n   - **Background**: Co-founder of PayPal, Thiel is known for his early investment in Facebook, which turned into one of the most profitable angel investments in history. He has a knack for identifying transformative technology companies.\n\n### 2. **Ron Conway**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Google, PayPal, Twitter, Airbnb, Dropbox\n   - **Background**: Often referred to as the \"Godfather of Silicon Valley,\" Conway has made hundreds of early-stage investments through his firm, SV Angel. His mentorship and network have been invaluable to countless startups.\n\n### 3. **Marc Andreessen**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Twitter, Facebook, Airbnb, Lyft\n   - **Background**: Co-founder of Netscape and the venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz, Andreessen has been a key figure in shaping the internet and software industries through both his entrepreneurial ventures and investments.\n\n### 4. **Naval Ravikant**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Twitter, Uber, Yammer, Salesforce\n   - **Background**: Ravikant, co-founder of AngelList, has been a prolific angel investor and has helped democratize angel investing through his platform. His investments span a wide range of successful tech companies.\n\n### 5. **Chris Sacca**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Twitter, Uber, Instagram, Kickstarter\n   - **Background**: Sacca, through his fund Lowercase Capital, made early investments in some of the most successful tech companies of the past decade. His investments in Twitter and Uber particularly stand out.\n\n### 6. **Paul Graham**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Dropbox, Airbnb, Stripe, Reddit\n   - **Background**: Co-founder of the startup accelerator Y Combinator, Graham has been instrumental in mentoring and funding some of the most successful startups. His essays on startups and entrepreneurship have also been highly influential.\n\n### 7. **Reid Hoffman**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Facebook, Airbnb, Flickr, Zynga\n   - **Background**: Co-founder of LinkedIn, Hoffman has been a key investor in numerous successful tech companies, leveraging his deep understanding of social networks and online platforms.\n\n### 8. **Esther Dyson**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Flickr, Del.icio.us, XCOR Aerospace\n   - **Background**: Dyson has been an active angel investor in the tech and space industries, known for her early investments in internet startups and her focus on emerging technologies.\n\n### 9. **Andy Bechtolsheim**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Google, Tableau Software, Alteryx\n   - **Background**: Co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Bechtolsheim made one of the first investments in Google, writing a $100,000 check to Larry Page and Sergey Brin before the company was officially incorporated.\n\n### 10. **Mike Maples Jr.**\n   - **Notable Investments**: Twitter, Lyft, Twitch, Okta\n   - **Background**: Maples, through his firm Floodgate, has been an early investor in several high-profile startups. His focus on \"thunder lizard\" companies has led to significant returns.\n\n### Honorable Mentions:\n- **Dave McClure**: Founder of 500 Startups, known for a wide portfolio of early-stage investments.\n- **Jason Calacanis**: Early investor in Uber, Robinhood, and other notable startups.\n- **Josh Kopelman**: Founder of First Round Capital, known for early investments in companies like Uber, Warby Parker, and Ring.\n\nThese investors have not only achieved remarkable financial success but have also played pivotal roles in nurturing and scaling some of the most innovative companies of our time.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
